A minimal readable rewrite is to normalize inputs once at the top, then keep the two output branches direct:

```ts
type PersonName = {
  first: string;
  last: string;
  nickname?: string;
};

export function makeLabel(p: PersonName, short: boolean): string {
  const first = p.first.trim();
  const last = p.last.trim();
  const nickname = p.nickname?.trim() || "";

  if (short) {
    return nickname || `${first} ${last}`;
  }

  return nickname ? `${last}, ${first} (${nickname})` : `${last}, ${first}`;
}
```

Cleanup boundary: do only local normalization inside this helper. Trim `first` and `last` when deriving output, collapse `nickname` to either a trimmed non-empty string or `""`, and stop there. Do not widen scope into shared utilities or type changes because the behavior is fully specified, local, synchronous, and already covered by passing tests.

Concise tests:
- `short=true` with nickname present: returns trimmed nickname.
- `short=true` with nickname absent: returns `"<trimmed first> <trimmed last>"`.
- `short=true` with nickname empty/whitespace: same as no nickname.
- `short=false` with nickname absent: returns `"<trimmed last>, <trimmed first>"`.
- `short=false` with nickname present: returns `"<trimmed last>, <trimmed first> (<trimmed nickname>)"`.
- Trimming case: surrounding whitespace on all three fields is removed exactly where specified.
- Preservation case: internal spaces are preserved; only leading/trailing whitespace is trimmed.
